"Fonthill Gifford, Wiltshire, England":"Fonthill Gifford, Wiltshire, England","Morayshire, Scotland":"Elginshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1084–1114":"1084–1114","1083–Male":"1083–Deceased","1085–Male":"1085–Deceased","1087–1129":"1087–1129","1115–1177":"1115–1177","1053–1135":"1053–1135","1052–1098":"1052–1098","about 1081":"about 1081","1098":"1098","1087":"1087","1086":"1086","1053":"1053","1096":"1096","1052":"1052","1085":"1085","1084":"1084","1083":"1083","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1115":"1115","1114":"1114","1135":"1135","1177":"1177","Badenoch, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Badenoch, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Fonthill Gifford, Wiltshire, England":"Fonthill Gifford, Wiltshire, England","Morayshire, Scotland":"Elginshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Comyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English, Irish:  see  Cumming  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cumming","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): most probably a habitational name from Bosc-Benard-Commin in Eure, France. This place lies on the edge of the Forêt de Rouvray, near Rouen, in the heart of the district from which came numerous Domesday barons, and so is much more likely to be the source of the name than Comines in Nord. The name is also possibly derived from the personal name <i>Cumin</i>, which is found in Norfolk, Lincolnshire, and Yorkshire in the 12th and 13th centuries and may be of Breton origin, according to Reaney. Compare Old Breton <i>Cunmin</i>, which also appears as <i>Cumin</i>, and is from <i>con-</i> ‘hound’ with an uncertain second element, perhaps the <i>min</i> ‘edge’ which is found in other personal names.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cuimín</b> (or <b>Ó Cuimín</b>) ‘son (or ‘descendant’) of <i>Cuimín</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>cam</i> ‘crooked’. There was a 7th-century abbot of Iona named <i>Cumin</i>. In Scotland, this Irish surname became confused with the Norman name.","History: A notable bearer of the Norman surname is Wilhelmus Comyn, Bishop of Durham, who came north to Scotland with King David I in 1124 and was appointed Chancellor of Scotland. He established his nephew Richard in Tynedale and Roxburghshire, and Richard also rose to be Chancellor of Scotland. The Comyn or Cumming family gained the earldoms of Buchan and Menteith and rose to be the most powerful noble family in Scotland in the century before the rise of King Robert Bruce."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":2,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":12,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":22,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William De Comyn Constable Of Scotland was born in 1084, in Fonthill Gifford, Wiltshire, England, his father, John de Comyn, was 31 and his mother, Sybil de Gifford, was 32. He had at least 1 son. In 1141, his occupation is listed as bishop of durham. He died in 1114, in Elginshire, Scotland, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1084–1114":"1084–1114","1083–Male":"1083–Surnud","1085–Male":"1085–Surnud","1087–1129":"1087–1129","1115–1177":"1115–1177","1053–1135":"1053–1135","1052–1098":"1052–1098","about 1081":"umbes 1081","1098":"1098","1087":"1087","1086":"1086","1053":"1053","1096":"1096","1052":"1052","1085":"1085","1084":"1084","1083":"1083","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1115":"1115","1114":"1114","1135":"1135","1177":"1177","Badenoch, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Badenoch, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Fonthill Gifford, Wiltshire, England":"Fonthill Gifford, Wiltshire, England","Morayshire